ladders.explanation:
This basic operation computes the absolute difference between two numbers, which is the positive distance between them regardless of which is larger. The intuition is that difference can be measured in two ways: signed difference (a-b) which indicates direction and magnitude, or absolute difference |a-b| which only measures magnitude. For problems involving distance or gap between values, absolute difference is typically needed because we care about the size of the gap, not which value is larger. Mathematically, |a-b| = a-b if a≥b, or b-a if b>a. In programming, we use the abs() function or implement it manually with conditional logic. This operation is fundamental to the adjacent difference problem because we want the magnitude of change between consecutive elements, not whether the sequence is increasing or decreasing. This connects to L3 as array traversal provides the pairs of numbers to difference. For L5, this builds on basic arithmetic. Common mistakes include: forgetting to take absolute value (getting negative differences), integer overflow with large numbers, and precision issues with floating point. The absolute difference operation has wide applications beyond this problem - in statistics (mean absolute deviation), geometry (distance), signal processing (amplitude change), and many other domains where magnitude of change matters more than direction.

Step-by-step algorithm:
1. If a ≥ b: return a - b
2. Else: return b - a

Or simply: return abs(a - b)

Time: O(1), Space: O(1)

Real code pattern:
def absolute_difference(a, b):
    return abs(a - b)

# Or manually:
def absolute_difference_manual(a, b):
    if a >= b:
        return a - b
    else:
        return b - a
